Introduction

The agent must use a map it is given to plan a path through the maze from the starting location $S$ to the goal location $G$. This is a planing exercise for a goal-based agent, so you do not need to implement an environment, just use the map to search for a path. Once the plan is made, the agent in a deterministic environment (i.e., the transition function is deterministic with the outcome of each state/action pair fixed and no randomness) can just follow the path and does not need to care about the percepts. This is also called an open-loop system. The execution phase is trivial and can be executed using a model-based reflex agent that ignores all percepts and just follows the plan. We do not implement it in this exercise.

Given that the agent has a complete and correct map, the environment is fully observable, discrete, deterministic, and known. Remember:

  • Fully observable means that the agent can see its state and what the available actions are. That means the percepts contain the complete current state. Here, during planning, the agent always sees its x and y coordinates on the map and also seeks when it has reached the goal state.
  • Discrete means that we have a finite set of states. The maze has a finite set of squares the agent can be in.
  • Deterministic means that the transition function contains no randomness. An action in a state will always produce the same result. Going south from the start state always will lead to the same square.
  • Know means that the agent knows the complete transition function. The agent has the map and therefore knows how its position changes when it walks in a direction.

Tree search algorithm implementations that you find online typically come from data structures courses and have a different aim than AI tree search. These algorithms assume that you already have a tree in memory. We are interested in dynamically creating a search tree with the aim of finding a good/the best path from the root note to the goal state. Follow the pseudo code presented in the text book (and replicated in the slides) closely. Ideally, we would like to search only a small part of the maze, i.e., create a search tree with as few nodes as possible.

Several mazes for this exercise are stored as text files. Here is the small example maze:

Tree structure

Here is an implementation of the basic node structure for the search algorithms (see Fig 3.7 on page 73). I have added a method that extracts the path from the root node to the current node. It can be used to get the path when the search is completed.

In[]:
class Node:
    def __init__(self, pos, parent, action, cost):
        self.pos = tuple(pos)    # the state; positions are (row,col)
        self.parent = parent     # reference to parent node. None means root node.
        self.action = action     # action used in the transition function (root node has None)
        self.cost = cost         # for uniform cost this is the depth. It is also g(n) for A* search

    def __str__(self):
        return f"Node - pos = {self.pos}; action = {self.action}; cost = {self.cost}"

    def get_path_from_root(self):
        """returns nodes on the path from the root to the current node."""
        node = self
        path = [node]

        while not node.parent is None:
            node = node.parent
            path.append(node)

        path.reverse()

        return(path)

If needed, then you can add more fields to the class like the heuristic value $h(n)$ or $f(n)$.

Examples for how to create and use a tree and information on memory management can be found here.

Task 1: Defining the search problem and determining the problem size [10 Points]

Define the components of the search problem:

  • Initial state
  • Actions
  • Transition model
  • Goal state
  • Path cost

Use verbal descriptions, variables and equations as appropriate.

Note: You can swich the next block from code to Markdown and use formating.

Initial State: the tile where agent begine to navigate the maze notated as S (start)

Actions: N, S, W, E

Transition Model: move from tile A to tile B

Goal State: reach tile defined as G (goal)

Path Cost: each action has the same cost, let's say c, then path cost = c*p where p is the number of actions taken to complete the given path

Give some estimates for the problem size:

  • $n$: state space size
  • $d$: depth of the optimal solution
  • $m$: maximum depth of tree
  • $b$: maximum branching factor

Describe how you would determin these values for a given maze.

$n$: number of tiles/sqaures in the maze (depends on maze size = x * y)

$d$: best case bounded by x * y

$m$: worst case also bounded by x * y

$b$: 4 (based on number of actions, in this case, NSWE)

In[]:
actions = ['N', 'E', 'S', 'W']

def result(pos, action):
  loc = list(pos)
  if (action == 'N'):
    loc[0] -= 1
  elif (action == 'S'):
    loc[0] += 1
  elif (action == 'W'):
    loc[1] -= 1
  elif (action == 'E'):
    loc[1] += 1
  return tuple(loc)

Task 2: Uninformed search: Breadth-first and depth-first [40 Points]

Implement these search strategies. Follow the pseudocode in the textbook/slides. You can use the tree structure shown above to extract the final path from your solution.

Read the following important notes carefully:

  • You can find maze solving implementations online that use the map to store information. While this is an effective idea for this two-dimensional navigation problem, it typically cannot be used for other search problems. Therefore, follow the textbook and do not store information in the map. Only store information in the tree created during search, and use the reached and frontier data structures where appropriate.
  • DSF behavior can be implemented using the BFS tree search algorithm and simply changing the order in which the frontier is expanded (this is equivalent to best-first search with path length as the criterion to expand the next node). However, this would be a big mistake since it combines the bad space complexity of BFS with the bad time complexity of DFS! To take advantage of the significantly smaller memory footprint of DFS, you need to implement DFS in a different way without a reached data structure (often also called visited or explored) and by releasing the memory for nodes that are not needed anymore.
  • Since the proper implementation of DFS does not use a reached data structure, redundant path checking abilities are limited to cycle checking. You need to implement cycle checking since DSF is incomplete (produces an infinite loop) if cycles cannot be prevented. You will see in your experiments that cycle checking in open spaces is challenging.
In[]:
# Expand

def expand(maze, node):#, frontier):
  s = node.pos
  child_nodes = []
  path = [n.pos for n in node.get_path_from_root()]
  #frontier_pos = [x.pos for x in frontier]
  for action in actions:
    s2 = result(s, action)
    if s2 in path:
      continue
    # if s2 in frontier_pos:
    #   continue
    if (maze[s2[0],s2[1]] != 'X'):
      cost = node.cost + 1
      new_node = Node(s2, node, action, cost)
      child_nodes.append(new_node)
  return child_nodes

In[]:
def cycle(node, frontier):
  parent = node.parent
  # if parent.parent == None:
  #   return False
  while parent != None:
    if node.pos == parent.pos:
      return True
    else:
      parent = parent.parent

    #if in fortier remove
  for f in frontier:
    if f.pos == node.pos:
      frontier.remove(f)
      # print("remove: ", f.pos)
      #break
  return False

def DFS(maze, max_tries = 1000, animation = True, bonus = False):

How does BFS and DFS (without a reached data structure) deal with loops (cycles)?

In[]:
# Abandoned branches are removed from memory which results in cycle checking only for the current path.

Are your implementations complete and optimal? Explain why. What is the time and space complexity of each of your implementations? Especially discuss the difference in space complexity between BFS and DFS.

In[]:
# BFS:
  # Complete: yes
  # Optimal: yes, if cost is the same (which in this case it is)
            # it will return the path that first reaches the goal
  # Time: number of created nodes of O(b^d) where b = 4 and d = depth of the optimal solution
  # Space: stored nodes of O(b^d)
# DFS:
  # Complete: only in finite spaces, otherwise incomplete for spaces with cycles
  # Optimal: no, it returns the first solutio it finds
  # Time:
  # Space: because there is no reached data structure and we delete abandoned bracnhes
          # there is less in memory resulting in space complexity of O(bm)

Task 3: Informed search: Implement greedy best-first search and A* search [20 Points]

You can use the map to estimate the distance from your current position to the goal using the Manhattan distance (see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taxicab_geometry) as a heuristic function. Both algorithms are based on Best-First search which requires only a small change from the BFS algorithm you have already implemented (see textbook/slides).

In[]:
import numpy as np
def manhattan(pos1, pos2):
    """returns the Manhattan distance between two positions"""
    return(np.sum(np.abs(np.subtract(pos1, pos2))))

#print(manhattan((0,0), (1,1)))

# BestFS definition based on BFS
import heapq
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
def BestFS(maze, f = 1, animation = True):
  order = 0
  max_depth = 0
  max_frontier = 0
  depth = 0
  start = mh.find_pos(maze, what = "S")
  goal = mh.find_pos(maze, what = "G")
  results = {'path': [], 'reached': [], 'actions': [], 'maze_anim': []}
  actions = []
  maze_snap = maze.copy()
  maze_anim = []
  node = Node(start, None, None, 0)
  if (node.pos == goal):
    return node
  frontier = []
  heapq.heappush(frontier, (manhattan(start, goal), order, node))
  reached = {start:node} # total number of nodes
  path = [[start]] # solution and path cost as length of path #########

  while (len(frontier) != 0):
    # print(curr_path)
    if len(frontier) > max_frontier: max_frontier = len(frontier) # max frontier
    node = (heapq.heappop(frontier))[2]
    maze_snap = maze_snap.copy()
    maze_snap[node.pos[0], node.pos[1]] = 'P'
    for child in expand(maze, node):
      child_depth = len(child.get_path_from_root())
      child.cost = child_depth
      #print("child cost: ", child_depth)
      #new_path = curr_path
      #print(depth)
      #depth += 1 # track depth
      s = child.pos
      if (child.pos == goal):
        maze_snap[p.pos[0], p.pos[1]] = 'P'
        maze_snap[start[0], start[1]] = 'S'
        maze_snap[goal[0], goal[1]] = 'G'
      #mh.show_maze(maze_snap)
        maze_anim.append(maze_snap)
        if animation:
          results['reached'] = reached
          results['actions'] = actions
          results['path'] = path[-1]
          results['maze_anim'] = maze_anim
          # for mz in maze_anim:
          #   mh.show_maze(mz)
          #   print(mh.maze_to_matrix(mz))
          return results, max_depth, max_frontier
      if (node.pos == goal):
        curr_path = node.get_path_from_root()
        path.append([n.pos for n in curr_path])
        if animation:
          results['reached'] = reached
          results['actions'] = actions
          results['path'] = path[-1]
          results['maze_anim'] = maze_anim
          return results, max_depth, max_frontier
      if len(maze_anim) > 1: maze_snap = maze_reset
      if (s not in reached) or (child.cost < reached[s].cost):
        reached[s] = child

        #print(child_depth)
        heapq.heappush(frontier, (manhattan(child.pos, goal), order, child)) ########### manhattan
        order += 1
        actions.append(child.action)
        maze_snap[s[0], s[1]] = 'F'
      curr_path = node.get_path_from_root()
      if len(curr_path) > depth: depth = len(curr_path)
      path.append([n.pos for n in curr_path])
      for p in curr_path:
        if maze_snap[p.pos[0], p.pos[1]] != 'F':
          maze_snap[p.pos[0], p.pos[1]] = 'P'
      maze_snap[start[0], start[1]] = 'S'
      maze_snap[goal[0], goal[1]] = 'G'
      #mh.show_maze(maze_snap)
      maze_anim.append(maze_snap)
      maze_reset = maze_snap.copy()
      for p in curr_path:
        maze_reset[p.pos[0], p.pos[1]] = '.'
      maze_snap[start[0], start[1]] = 'S'
      maze_snap[goal[0], goal[1]] = 'G'
      # if (node.pos[0], node.pos[1]) != (start[0], start[1]):
      #   maze_snap[node.pos[0], node.pos[1]] = '.'
      if depth > max_depth: max_depth = depth

  # if animation:
  #   results['reached'] = reached
  #   results['actions'] = actions
  #   results['path'] = path
  #   results['maze_anim'] = maze_anim
  #   return results results, max_depth, total_nodes, max_frontier
  return -1

# A* search based on BestFS
import heapq
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
def A(maze, f = 1, animation = True):
  order = 0
  max_depth = 0
  max_frontier = 0
  depth = 0
  start = mh.find_pos(maze, what = "S")
  goal = mh.find_pos(maze, what = "G")
  results = {'path': [], 'reached': [], 'actions': [], 'maze_anim': []}
  actions = []
  maze_snap = maze.copy()
  maze_anim = []
  node = Node(start, None, None, 0)
  if (node.pos == goal):
    return node
  frontier = []
  heapq.heappush(frontier, (manhattan(start, goal), order, node))
  reached = {start:node} # total number of nodes
  path = [[start]] # solution and path cost as length of path #########

  while (len(frontier) != 0):
    # print(curr_path)
    if len(frontier) > max_frontier: max_frontier = len(frontier) # max frontier
    node = (heapq.heappop(frontier))[2]
    maze_snap = maze_snap.copy()
    maze_snap[node.pos[0], node.pos[1]] = 'P'
    for child in expand(maze, node):
      child_depth = len(child.get_path_from_root())
      child.cost = child_depth
      s = child.pos
      if (child.pos == goal):
        maze_snap[p.pos[0], p.pos[1]] = 'P'
        maze_snap[start[0], start[1]] = 'S'
        maze_snap[goal[0], goal[1]] = 'G'
        maze_anim.append(maze_snap)
        if animation:
          results['reached'] = reached
          results['actions'] = actions
          results['path'] = path[-1]
          results['maze_anim'] = maze_anim
          return results, max_depth, max_frontier
      if (node.pos == goal):
        curr_path = node.get_path_from_root()
        path.append([n.pos for n in curr_path])
        if animation:
          results['reached'] = reached
          results['actions'] = actions
          results['path'] = path[-1]
          results['maze_anim'] = maze_anim
          return results, max_depth, max_frontier
      if len(maze_anim) > 1: maze_snap = maze_reset
      if (s not in reached) or (child.cost < reached[s].cost):
        reached[s] = child
        heapq.heappush(frontier, (manhattan(child.pos, goal) + child_depth, order, child)) ########### manhattan
        order += 1
        actions.append(child.action)
        maze_snap[s[0], s[1]] = 'F'
      curr_path = node.get_path_from_root()
      if len(curr_path) > depth: depth = len(curr_path)
      path.append([n.pos for n in curr_path])
      for p in curr_path:
        if maze_snap[p.pos[0], p.pos[1]] != 'F':
          maze_snap[p.pos[0], p.pos[1]] = 'P'
      maze_snap[start[0], start[1]] = 'S'
      maze_snap[goal[0], goal[1]] = 'G'
      maze_anim.append(maze_snap)
      maze_reset = maze_snap.copy()
      for p in curr_path:
        maze_reset[p.pos[0], p.pos[1]] = '.'
      maze_snap[start[0], start[1]] = 'S'
      maze_snap[goal[0], goal[1]] = 'G'
      if depth > max_depth: max_depth = depth
  return -1

Are your implementations complete and optimal? What is the time and space complexity?

In[]:
# BestFS:
  # complete: Yes, Best-first search is complete in finite spaces liek the mazes provided.
  # optimal:
  # time: Worst case: O(bm) (like DFS) and Best case: O(bm)  If (n) is 100% accurate we only expand a single path,
        # where b is max branching factor and m is max depth.
  # space: same as time complexity ^

# A*:
  # complete: Yes
  # optimal: Yes, No other tree-based search algorithm that uses the same heuristic can expand fewer nodes and still be
            # guaranteed to find the optimal solution.
  # time: Number of nodes for which (n)  * in the worst case (^) like BFS.
  # space: Same as time complexity ^

How to deal with issues:

  • Your implementation returns unexpected results: Try to debug and fix the code. Visualizing the maze, the current path and the frontier after every step is very helpful. If the code still does not work, then mark the result with an asterisk (*) and describe the issue below the table.

  • Your implementation cannot consistently solve a specific maze and ends up in an infinite loop: Debug (likely your frontier and cycle checking for DFS are the issue). If it is a shortcoming of the algorithm/implementation, then put "N/A*" in the results table and describe why this is happening.

    # Add an 'Algorithm' column for identification
    df['Algorithm'] = algorithm_name
    return df

        algorithm_data = maze_data[maze_data['Algorithm'] == algorithm].iloc[0]

        # Print the row for this algorithm
        print(f"| {algorithm:<9} | {algorithm_data['Path Cost']:<9} | {algorithm_data['Reached']:<18} | "
              f"{algorithm_data['Max Depth']:<14} | {algorithm_data['Nodes in Memory']:<24} | "
              f"{algorithm_data['Max Frontier']:<17} |")
    print("\n")

    # Iterate through each algorithm in the maze data
    for algorithm in maze_data['Algorithm'].unique():
        algorithm_data = maze_data[maze_data['Algorithm'] == algorithm].iloc[0]

        # Append the result as a dictionary to the results list
        results.append({
            'Maze': maze,
            'Algorithm': algorithm,
            'Path Cost': algorithm_data['Path Cost'],
            'Reached': algorithm_data['Reached'],
            'Max Depth': algorithm_data['Max Depth'],
            'Max Frontier': algorithm_data['Max Frontier'],
            'Nodes in Memory': algorithm_data['Nodes in Memory']
        })

# Convert the results list into a DataFrame
final_df = pd.DataFrame(results)

# Now `final_df` contains all the results
#print(final_df)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Set the style for seaborn (optional)
sns.set(style="whitegrid")

# Get the unique maze types
maze_types = final_df['Maze'].unique()

# Define the features to be plotted
features = ['Path Cost', 'Reached', 'Max Depth', 'Max Frontier', 'Nodes in Memory']

# Create a figure with 3x3 subplots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 3, figsize=(18, 18))

# Flatten the axes array for easier iteration
axes = axes.flatten()

# Set the y-axis limits (same for all plots)
y_limit_min = final_df[features].min().min()
y_limit_max = 250#final_df[features].max().max()

# Iterate through each maze type and plot on the corresponding subplot
for i, maze in enumerate(maze_types):
    ax = axes[i]

    # Filter the data for the current maze type
    maze_data = final_df[final_df['Maze'] == maze]

    # Create a bar plot for each feature, grouped by Algorithm
    sns.barplot(x="Algorithm", y="Path Cost", hue="Algorithm", data=maze_data, ax=ax)

    # Set the title of the plot for the current maze
    ax.set_title(f'{maze} Maze')

    # Set the y-axis limit (same for all plots)
    ax.set_ylim(y_limit_min, y_limit_max)

    # Rotate x-axis labels for better readability
    # ax.set_xticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45, ha="right")
# Adjust the layout so the plots don't overlap
plt.tight_layout()

# Show the plot
plt.show()

IDS

Implement IDS (iterative deepening search) using your DFS implementation. Test IDS on the mazes above. You may run into some issues with mazes with open spaces. If you cannot resolve the issus, then report and discuss what causes the problems.

In[]:
def IDS(problem):
  for depth in range(1, 1000):
    result = DFS(problem, depth)
    if result != "cutoff":
      return result
In[]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
def DFS(maze, max_tries = 1000, animation = True):
  max_depth = 0
  max_frontier = 0
  start = mh.find_pos(maze, what = "S")
  goal = mh.find_pos(maze, what = "G")
  results = {'path': [], 'reached': [], 'actions': [], 'maze_anim': []}
  path = [] # solution and path cost as length of path
  actions = []
  maze_snap = maze.copy()
  maze_anim = []
  node = Node(start, None, None, 0)
  if (node.pos == goal):
    return node
  frontier = [node]
  reached = [start] # total number of nodes

  while (len(frontier) != 0):# and (len(frontier[-1].get_path_from_root()) < max_tries):
    # # # print("again")
    if len(frontier) > max_frontier: max_frontier = len(frontier) # max frontier
    node = frontier.pop()
    # print("popped: ", node.pos)
    reached.append(node.pos)

    depth = 0

    d = len(node.get_path_from_root())
    if d > max_tries:
      # if len(frontier) > 1:
      #   depth_list = [len(f.get_path_from_root()) for f in frontier]
      #   #print(depth_list)
      #   lowest_depth = min(depth_list)
      #   while len(frontier[-1].get_path_from_root())>lowest_depth:
      #     frontier.pop()
      #frontier.pop()
      continue
    if (node.pos == goal):
        if animation:
          maze_anim[0][start[0], start[1]] = 'S'
          maze_anim[0][goal[0], goal[1]] = 'G'
          results['reached'] = reached
          results['actions'] = actions
          results['path'] = node.get_path_from_root()#path
          results['maze_anim'] = maze_anim
          return results, max_depth, max_frontier

    if (cycle(node, frontier)) == False:
        for child in expand(maze, node):#, frontier):
          if len(maze_anim) > 1: maze_snap = maze_reset

          s = child.pos
          for c in frontier:
              if c.pos == child.pos:
                  frontier.remove(c)
              # if c in frontier:
              #  frontier.remove(c)
          if (child not in frontier) and (s not in child.get_path_from_root()):
            frontier.append(child)
            # print("appended: ", child.pos)
            actions.append(child.action)
            maze_snap[s[0], s[1]] = 'F'

        curr_path = node.get_path_from_root()
        if len(curr_path) > depth: depth = len(curr_path)
        path.append([n.pos for n in curr_path])
        for p in curr_path:
          #if maze_snap[p.pos[0], p.pos[1]] != 'F':
            maze_snap[p.pos[0], p.pos[1]] = 'P'
        maze_snap[start[0], start[1]] = 'S'
        maze_snap[goal[0], goal[1]] = 'G'
        # mh.show_maze(maze_snap) #######################
        maze_anim.append(maze_snap)
        maze_reset = maze_snap.copy()
        for p in curr_path:
          maze_reset[p.pos[0], p.pos[1]] = ' '
          maze_reset[start[0], start[1]] = 'S'
          maze_reset[goal[0], goal[1]] = 'G'
        if depth > max_depth: max_depth = depth

        if (child.pos == goal):
            ## mh.show_maze(maze_snap)
            maze_snap[child.pos[0], child.pos[1]] = 'P'
            maze_snap[start[0], start[1]] = 'S'
            maze_snap[goal[0], goal[1]] = 'G'
            # mh.show_maze(maze_snap) #########################
            maze_anim.append(maze_snap)
            if animation:
              results['reached'] = reached
              results['actions'] = actions
              results['path'] = path[-1]
              results['maze_anim'] = maze_anim

              return results, max_depth, max_frontier

  return "cutoff"

Discussion

IDS seems to work better for some of the mazes where the goal is clsoer to the start. However, my implementation seems to be flawed as the frontier does not get properly handled and many froniter nodes remain even after that depth shoudl have been removed and replaced with a new path to be explored. With more time I would find the error (likely something small but well hidden in my very messy ugly code) and there would be an imrpovement in the open space when using IDS as it would not continue exploring in seemingly random areas outside of the defined algorithm.

Multiple Goals

Create a few mazes with multiple goals by adding one or two more goals to the medium size maze. The agent is done when it finds one of the goals. Solve the maze with your implementations for DFS, BFS, and IDS. Run experiments to show which implementations find the optimal solution and which do not. Discuss why that is the case.

#for bonus
def find_goal(maze):
  positions = []
  for i in range(len(maze)):
      for j in range(len(maze[i])):
          if maze[i][j] == "G":
              positions.append((i, j))
  return positions

def BFS_b(maze, animation = True):
  max_depth = 0
  max_frontier = 0
  depth = 0
  start = mh.find_pos(maze, what = "S")
  goals = find_goal(maze)
  results = {'path': [], 'reached': [], 'actions': [], 'maze_anim': []}
  actions = []
  maze_snap = maze.copy()
  maze_anim = []
  node = Node(start, None, None, 0)
  if (node.pos in goals):
    return node
  frontier = [node]
  reached = [start] # total number of nodes
  path = [[start]] # solution and path cost as length of path #########

  while (len(frontier) != 0):
    # print(curr_path)
    if len(frontier) > max_frontier: max_frontier = len(frontier) # max frontier
    node = frontier.pop()
    maze_snap = maze_snap.copy()
    maze_snap[node.pos[0], node.pos[1]] = 'P'
    for child in expand(maze, node):#, frontier):
      #new_path = curr_path
      #print(depth)
      #depth += 1 # track depth
      s = child.pos
      if (child.pos in goals) or (maze[child.pos[0], child.pos[1]] == 'G'):
        maze_snap[p.pos[0], p.pos[1]] = 'P'
        maze_snap[start[0], start[1]] = 'S'
        maze_snap[child.pos[0], child.pos[1]] = 'G'
      #mh.show_maze(maze_snap)
        maze_anim.append(maze_snap)
        if animation:
          results['reached'] = reached
          results['actions'] = actions
          results['path'] = path[-1]
          results['maze_anim'] = maze_anim
          # for mz in maze_anim:
          #   mh.show_maze(mz)
          #   print(mh.maze_to_matrix(mz))
        return results, max_depth, max_frontier
      if (node.pos in goals) or (maze[node.pos[0], node.pos[1]] == 'G'):
        curr_path = node.get_path_from_root()
        path.append([n.pos for n in curr_path])
        if animation:
          results['reached'] = reached
          results['actions'] = actions
          results['path'] = path[-1]
          results['maze_anim'] = maze_anim
        return results, max_depth, max_frontier
      if len(maze_anim) > 1: maze_snap = maze_reset
      if s not in reached:
        reached.append(s)
        frontier.insert(0, child)
        actions.append(child.action)
        maze_snap[s[0], s[1]] = 'F'
      curr_path = node.get_path_from_root()
      if len(curr_path) > depth: depth = len(curr_path)
      path.append([n.pos for n in curr_path])
      for p in curr_path:
        if maze_snap[p.pos[0], p.pos[1]] != 'F':
          maze_snap[p.pos[0], p.pos[1]] = 'P'
      maze_snap[start[0], start[1]] = 'S'
      #maze_snap[goal[0], goal[1]] = 'G'
      #mh.show_maze(maze_snap)
      maze_anim.append(maze_snap)
      maze_reset = maze_snap.copy()
      for p in curr_path:
        maze_reset[p.pos[0], p.pos[1]] = '.'
      maze_snap[start[0], start[1]] = 'S'
      #maze_snap[goal[0], goal[1]] = 'G'
      # if (node.pos[0], node.pos[1]) != (start[0], start[1]):
      #   maze_snap[node.pos[0], node.pos[1]] = '.'

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
def DFS_b(maze, max_tries = 1000, animation = True, bonus = False):
  max_depth = 0
  max_frontier = 0
  start = mh.find_pos(maze, what = "S")
  goals = find_goal(maze)
  results = {'path': [], 'reached': [], 'actions': [], 'maze_anim': []}
  path = [] # solution and path cost as length of path
  actions = []
  maze_snap = maze.copy()
  maze_anim = []
  node = Node(start, None, None, 0)
  if (node.pos in goals):
    return node
  frontier = [node]
  reached = [start] # total number of nodes
  #visited = []
  # # print((node in visited))
  #visited.append(node)
  # # print(node in visited)

  while (len(frontier) != 0):
    # # # print("again")
    if len(frontier) > max_frontier: max_frontier = len(frontier) # max frontier
    node = frontier.pop()
    # print("popped: ", node.pos)
    reached.append(node.pos)

    depth = 0

    d = len(node.get_path_from_root())
    if d > max_tries:
      # if len(frontier) > 1:
      #   depth_list = [len(f.get_path_from_root()) for f in frontier]
      #   #print(depth_list)
      #   lowest_depth = min(depth_list)
      #   while len(frontier[-1].get_path_from_root())>lowest_depth:
      #     frontier.pop()
      #frontier.pop()
      continue

    if node.pos in goals:
      curr_path = node.get_path_from_root()
      path.append([n.pos for n in curr_path])
      if animation:
        results['reached'] = reached
        results['actions'] = actions
        results['path'] = path[-1]
        results['maze_anim'] = maze_anim
      return results, max_depth, max_frontier
    # if depth > max_tries:
    #   results['reached'] = reached
    #   results['actions'] = actions
    #   results['path'] = path
    #   results['maze_anim'] = maze_anim
    #   return results, max_depth, max_frontier
    #else:

    if (cycle(node, frontier)) == False:
       # # # print("trying")
        for child in expand(maze, node):#, frontier):
          if len(maze_anim) > 1: maze_snap = maze_reset

          s = child.pos
          for c in frontier:
              if c.pos == child.pos:
                  frontier.remove(c)
              # if c in frontier:
              #  frontier.remove(c)
          if (child not in frontier) and (s not in child.get_path_from_root()):
            frontier.append(child)
            # print("appended: ", child.pos)
            actions.append(child.action)
            maze_snap[s[0], s[1]] = 'F'

        curr_path = node.get_path_from_root()
        if len(curr_path) > depth: depth = len(curr_path)
        path.append([n.pos for n in curr_path])
        for p in curr_path:
          #if maze_snap[p.pos[0], p.pos[1]] != 'F':
            maze_snap[p.pos[0], p.pos[1]] = 'P'
        maze_snap[start[0], start[1]] = 'S'
        #maze_snap[goal[0], goal[1]] = 'G'
        # mh.show_maze(maze_snap) #######################
        maze_anim.append(maze_snap)
        maze_reset = maze_snap.copy()
        for p in curr_path:
          maze_reset[p.pos[0], p.pos[1]] = ' '
          maze_reset[start[0], start[1]] = 'S'
          #maze_reset[goal[0], goal[1]] = 'G'
        if depth > max_depth: max_depth = depth

        if child.pos in goals:
          maze_snap[p.pos[0], p.pos[1]] = 'P'
          maze_snap[start[0], start[1]] = 'S'
          maze_snap[child.pos[0], child.pos[1]] = 'G'
          #mh.show_maze(maze_snap)
          maze_anim.append(maze_snap)
          if animation:
            results['reached'] = reached
            results['actions'] = actions
            results['path'] = path[-1]
            results['maze_anim'] = maze_anim
              # for mz in maze_anim:
              #   mh.show_maze(mz)
              #   print(mh.maze_to_matrix(mz))
          return results, max_depth, max_frontier
  return "cutoff"
In[]:
def IDS_b(problem):
  for depth in range(1, 1000):
    result = DFS_b(problem, depth)
    if result != "cutoff":
      return result

IDS_bonus = {"Path Cost":[], "Reached":[], "Max Frontier": [], "Max Depth":[]}
DFS_bonus = {"Path Cost":[], "Reached":[], "Max Frontier": [], "Max Depth":[]}
BFS_bonus = {"Path Cost":[], "Reached":[], "Max Frontier": [], "Max Depth":[]}

for m in mazes:
  #mh.show_maze(m)
  #IDS
  maze_result, max_depth, max_frontier = IDS_b(m)
  #print("Path Cost: ", len(maze_result['path']) - 1, "\nTotal Number of Nodes: ", len(maze_result['reached']), "\nMax Frontier: ", max_frontier, "\nMax Depth: ", max_depth - 1)
  IDS_bonus["Path Cost"].append(len(maze_result['path']) - 1)
  IDS_bonus["Reached"].append(len(maze_result['reached']))
  IDS_bonus["Max Frontier"].append(max_frontier)
  IDS_bonus["Max Depth"].append(max_depth)
#  mh.animate_maze(maze_result)

  #DFS
  maze_result, max_depth, max_frontier = DFS_b(m)
  #print("Path Cost: ", len(maze_result['path']) - 1, "\nTotal Number of Nodes: ", len(maze_result['reached']), "\nMax Frontier: ", max_frontier, "\nMax Depth: ", max_depth - 1)
  DFS_bonus["Path Cost"].append(len(maze_result['path']) - 1)
  DFS_bonus["Reached"].append(len(maze_result['reached']))
  DFS_bonus["Max Frontier"].append(max_frontier)
  DFS_bonus["Max Depth"].append(max_depth)
#  mh.animate_maze(maze_result)

  #BFS
  maze_result, max_depth, max_frontier = BFS_b(m)
  #print("Path Cost: ", len(maze_result['path']) - 1, "\nTotal Number of Nodes: ", len(maze_result['reached']), "\nMax Frontier: ", max_frontier, "\nMax Depth: ", max_depth - 1)
  BFS_bonus["Path Cost"].append(len(maze_result['path']) - 1)
  BFS_bonus["Reached"].append(len(maze_result['reached']))
  BFS_bonus["Max Frontier"].append(max_frontier)
  BFS_bonus["Max Depth"].append(max_depth)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

categories = ['Path Cost', 'Reached', 'Max Frontier', 'Max Depth']
values_1 = [np.mean(BFS_bonus[key]) for key in categories]
values_2 = [np.mean(DFS_bonus[key]) for key in categories]
values_3 = [np.mean(IDS_bonus[key]) for key in categories]

# Set up the plot
x = np.arange(len(categories))  # the label locations
width = 0.2  # the width of the bars

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))

# Plotting the bars for each dataset
bars1 = ax.bar(x - width, values_1, width, label='BFS')
bars2 = ax.bar(x, values_2, width, label='DFS')
bars3 = ax.bar(x + width, values_3, width, label='IDS')

# Labeling
ax.set_xlabel('Categories')
ax.set_ylabel('Values')
ax.set_title('Comparison of Data Across Categories')
ax.set_xticks(x)
ax.set_xticklabels(categories)
ax.legend()

# Display the plot
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Discussion

IDS seems to have the best performance as it combines the efficient features of both BFS and DFS (by iteratively checking to full depth in each "branch"/"direction") so BFS and DFS sometimes do as well but never better.

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to html

            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'qtpdf', 'qtpng', 'rst', 'script', 'slides', 'webpdf'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic', 'lab' and
            'classic'. You can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template lab mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.

More advanced tasks to think about

Intersection as states

Instead of defining each square as a state, use only intersections as states. Now the storage requirement is reduced, but the path length between two intersections can be different. If we use total path length measured as the number of squares as path cost, how can we make sure that BFS and iterative deepening search is optimal? Change the code to do so.

Unknown Maze

What happens if the agent does not know the layout of the maze in advance? This means that the agent faces an unknown environment, where it does not know the transition function. How does the environment look then (PEAS description)? How would you implement a rational agent to solve the maze? What if the agent still has a GPS device to tell the distance to the goal?
